{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659638"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20881"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20881"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.62,0.1,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79505"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11793"},{"type":"tags","id":"12314"},{"type":"tags","id":"12706"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33125"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following genetic disorders is primarily caused by a defect in receptor-mediated endocytosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cystic fibrosis with impaired chloride channel function","Familial hypercholesterolaemia with defective LDL receptor function","Glucose-galactose malabsorption with defective SGLT1 transporter","Wilson disease with impaired copper ATPase activity","Bartter syndrome with defective sodium-potassium-chloride cotransport"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Efamilial hypercholesterolaemia with defective LDL receptor function\u003C/strong\u003E. This genetic disorder is characterized by mutations in the LDL receptor gene, resulting in impaired receptor-mediated endocytosis of LDL particles. The defective uptake of LDL cholesterol into cells leads to elevated plasma LDL cholesterol levels and predisposes affected individuals to premature atherosclerosis and cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystic fibrosis with impaired chloride channel function\u003C/strong\u003E - This disorder involves defects in the CFTR protein, which functions as a chloride channel. The primary defect is in ion transport across cell membranes, not receptor-mediated endocytosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-galactose malabsorption with defective SGLT1 transporter\u003C/strong\u003E - This disorder involves mutations in the sodium-glucose cotransporter (SGLT1), which is a membrane transport protein that facilitates active transport of glucose and galactose across the intestinal brush border. It is not a disorder of receptor-mediated endocytosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilson disease with impaired copper ATPase activity\u003C/strong\u003E - This disorder involves mutations in the ATP7B gene, which encodes a copper-transporting P-type ATPase. The defect affects copper transport and excretion, not receptor-mediated endocytosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBartter syndrome with defective sodium-potassium-chloride cotransport\u003C/strong\u003E - This disorder involves defects in various ion transporters in the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle, affecting renal salt reabsorption. It is not a disorder of receptor-mediated endocytosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFamilial hypercholesterolaemia represents a classic example of a genetic disorder affecting receptor-mediated endocytosis, where the defective LDL receptor fails to internalize LDL particles efficiently, resulting in elevated plasma cholesterol levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Receptor-mediated endocytosis is a cellular transport mechanism that allows specific molecules to enter cells via receptor binding and vesicle formation.","Familial hypercholesterolaemia is caused by mutations in the LDL receptor gene, resulting in defective receptor-mediated endocytosis of LDL particles.","Defects in receptor-mediated endocytosis lead to accumulation of substances in blood that would normally be cleared by cells."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 148"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79505"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20881"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79505"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:17:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:20:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13756"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10